    "In a bus topology, all devices connect to a central hub or switch — easy to manage and fault-isolate. In a star topology, all devices share a single communication line; a cable break can disrupt all nodes. In a ring topology, each node connects to two neighbors forming a loop; the ring is immune to single faults by default without requiring redundancy protocols. A tree topology is a fully meshed structure where every device connects directly to every other device, used in mission-critical military and aerospace networks.",
    "In a bus topology, all devices share a single communication line; it is simple but a cable break can disrupt all nodes. In a star topology, all devices connect to a central hub or switch — easy to manage and fault-isolate, most common in modern Ethernet. In a ring topology, each node connects to two neighbors forming a loop; data travels in one direction and the ring can be broken by a single fault unless redundancy is built in. A tree topology combines stars in a hierarchical structure, used in large industrial and building networks.",
