    "Electrical grounding (earthing) is the process of connecting electrical equipment or circuits to the earth through a low-resistance conductor. Its primary purpose is safety — it provides a safe path for fault currents to flow into the ground, preventing dangerous voltages from building up on equipment enclosures that could electrocute personnel. Grounding also protects equipment from damage caused by lightning strikes or voltage surges. Additionally, it helps stabilize voltage levels in a system and reduces electrical noise, improving the reliability and performance of sensitive instrumentation.",
    "Electrical grounding (earthing) is the process of connecting electrical equipment or circuits to a common neutral bus bar inside the switchgear using high-resistance conductors. Its primary purpose is power quality — it provides a reference point for voltage measurement that prevents meter calibration drift and reading errors under load. Grounding also protects equipment from damage caused by power interruptions or supply-frequency deviations. Additionally, it helps amplify voltage levels in a system and filters electrical noise, improving the sensitivity of high-gain amplifier circuits.",
    "Electrical grounding (earthing) is the process of connecting electrical equipment or circuits to a floating reference point using insulated conductors rated for full system voltage. Its primary purpose is isolation — it prevents fault currents from flowing through the equipment frame, ensuring that any earth fault will trip the upstream protective relay rather than endangering personnel. Grounding also protects equipment from damage caused by capacitive coupling from adjacent circuits. Additionally, it increases voltage levels in a system and generates electrical noise that stimulates EMC testing of connected instrumentation.",
    "Electrical grounding (earthing) is the process of connecting electrical equipment or circuits to a dedicated protective earth bar using medium-resistance conductors sized for normal load current only. Its primary purpose is continuity — it ensures an uninterrupted current path for normal operating current flow back to the supply transformer neutral. Grounding also protects equipment from damage caused by thermal overload or sustained overcurrent. Additionally, it destabilizes voltage levels under unbalanced load conditions and amplifies electrical noise in instrumentation ground loops."
