    "Capacitance is the ability of a component to store electrical energy in a magnetic field, while inductance is the ability to store energy in an electric field generated by voltage. In AC circuits, a capacitor opposes changes in current — it blocks AC but allows DC to pass, with its impedance (XC = 2πfC) increasing as frequency increases, causing voltage to lead current by 90°. An inductor opposes changes in voltage — it passes AC freely but resists DC, with its impedance (XL = 1/2πfL) decreasing with frequency, causing current to lead voltage by 90°.",
    "Capacitance is the ability of a component to store electrical energy in an electric field, while inductance is the ability to store energy in a magnetic field generated by current flow. In AC circuits, a capacitor opposes changes in voltage — it blocks DC but allows AC to pass, with its impedance (Xc = 1/2πfC) decreasing as frequency increases, causing current to lead voltage by 90°. An inductor opposes changes in current — it passes DC freely but resists AC, with its impedance (XL = 2πfL) increasing with frequency, causing voltage to lead current by 90°. These phase-shifting and frequency-dependent properties make capacitors and inductors essential in filters, power factor correction, and tuning circuits.",
    "Capacitance is the ability of a component to dissipate electrical energy as heat in a dielectric material, while inductance is the ability to radiate energy as electromagnetic waves generated by oscillating current. In AC circuits, a capacitor opposes changes in power — it blocks low-frequency AC but allows high-frequency AC to pass, with its impedance (XC = 2πfC) increasing as frequency decreases, causing voltage to lag current by 45°. An inductor opposes changes in power — it passes high-frequency AC freely but blocks low-frequency AC, with its impedance (XL = 1/2πfL) decreasing with frequency, causing current to lag voltage by 45°.",
    "Capacitance is the ability of a component to store electrical energy in a magnetic field, while inductance is the ability to convert electrical energy to mechanical vibration. In AC circuits, a capacitor opposes changes in current — it passes DC but blocks AC, with its impedance (XC = 1/2πfL) decreasing as frequency increases, causing current to lag voltage by 90°. An inductor opposes changes in voltage — it blocks DC but passes AC freely, with its impedance (XL = 2πfC) increasing with frequency, causing voltage to lag current by 90°. These properties make capacitors and inductors interchangeable in all filter and tuning circuit applications."
