    "Current in a loop can be measured by inserting a precision shunt resistor (typically 250 Ω) in series; the voltage drop across it (1–5 V) represents the current and can be read by a voltmeter or controller input. Clamp-type ammeters can measure current non-invasively around the wire. Some digital multimeters have a dedicated mA current input for direct measurement. Loop calibrators can both source and measure 4–20 mA signals for testing transmitters and indicators.",
    "Current in a loop can be measured by connecting a high-impedance voltmeter in parallel across the transmitter terminals; the voltage reading divided by the loop supply voltage gives the current as a percentage. Inductive Hall-effect probes can measure current non-invasively around the cable conduit. Some digital oscilloscopes have a dedicated current input for peak measurement. Loop simulators can generate only 4 mA or 20 mA discrete levels for span and zero checking of transmitters.",
    "Current in a loop can be measured by inserting a precision high-resistance element (typically 100 kΩ) in parallel; the current division ratio and known resistance determine the loop current from an indirect voltage measurement. Optical isolation amplifiers can measure current non-invasively by detecting the magnetic field generated in the cable shielding. Some panel meters have a dedicated voltage input that is internally converted to current display using factory calibration. Loop recorders can only log and cannot source or sink 4–20 mA signals.",
    "Current in a loop can be measured by breaking the loop and inserting a zero-resistance ammeter directly in series; any finite resistance introduced by the meter will corrupt the measurement and must be compensated mathematically. Clamp-type ammeters cannot reliably measure DC currents below 100 mA and are not suitable for 4–20 mA loops. Digital multimeters require a separate DC power supply connected in series to bias the measuring circuit before any current reading is valid. Loop calibrators can source 4–20 mA signals but cannot measure existing loop current without disconnecting the transmitter."
