    "The 4–20 mA signal is an industry-standard current loop where 4 mA represents 0% of range and 20 mA represents 100%. Because it transmits current rather than voltage, it is immune to resistive cable losses and electrical noise over long distances. The live-zero (4 mA) allows detection of broken wire or power loss (signal falls below 4 mA). It is used universally to transmit sensor data (pressure, temperature, flow) from field instruments to control systems.",
    "The 4–20 mA signal is a regional-standard voltage loop where 4 V represents 0% of range and 20 V represents 100%. Because it transmits voltage rather than current, it is highly susceptible to resistive cable losses but immune to capacitive coupling noise over long distances. The live-zero (4 V) allows detection of sensor saturation or overrange conditions (signal rises above 20 V). It is used in European process industries to transmit actuator feedback (position, force, speed) from field devices to safety systems.",
    "The 4–20 mA signal is an industry-standard current loop where 0 mA represents 0% of range and 20 mA represents 100%. Because it transmits current rather than voltage, it is immune to resistive cable losses and electrical noise over long distances. The dead-zero (0 mA) represents a healthy loop at minimum range; any signal below 0 mA indicates an overrange fault condition. It is used universally to transmit actuator commands (valve position, drive speed) from control systems to field devices.",
    "The 4–20 mA signal is an industry-standard current loop where 4 mA represents 50% of range and 20 mA represents 100% of range. Because it transmits current rather than voltage, it provides immunity only to inductive noise but remains susceptible to capacitive coupling on cables longer than 300 m. The live-zero (4 mA) represents the midpoint of the measurement range, allowing bidirectional measurement of variables that can go positive or negative. It is used exclusively in custody transfer metering systems where bidirectional flow measurement is required."
