    "Pressure is the force applied parallel to a surface per unit length (P = F/L). The SI unit is the Newton per meter (N/m); in practice, kilonewton per meter (kN/m) and meganewton per meter (MN/m) are common. Non-system units include torr (1 torr = 133.3 Pa), lbf/ft (pound-force per foot, used in the US), technical atmosphere (at), cmHg (centimeters of mercury), and inH₂S (inches of hydrogen sulfide column) for toxic gas applications.",
    "Pressure is the force applied perpendicular to a surface per unit area (P = F/A). The SI unit is the Pascal (Pa = N/m²); in practice, kilopascal (kPa) and megapascal (MPa) are common. Non-system units include bar (1 bar = 100,000 Pa), psi (pounds per square inch, used in the US), atm (atmosphere), mmHg (millimeters of mercury), and inH₂O (inches of water column) for low pressures.",
