    question: "Explain the purpose and operating principle of a differential pressure (DP) transmitter.",
    options: [
    "A DP transmitter measures the pressure difference between two points (high-side and low-side connections) and outputs a proportional 4–20 mA signal. Internally, both pressures act on opposite sides of a sensing diaphragm or capsule; the deflection proportional to the pressure difference is converted to an electrical signal. DP transmitters are used to measure flow (via orifice plates), level (via hydrostatic head), and pressure drop across filters or heat exchangers.",
    "A DP transmitter measures the absolute pressure at a single high-side connection and compares it to an internal factory-set reference vacuum to output a proportional 4–20 mA signal. Internally, the process pressure acts on one side of a sensing capsule while the other side is sealed at a calibrated vacuum; the deflection proportional to the absolute pressure is converted to an electrical signal. DP transmitters are used exclusively to measure gas-phase pressure in vacuum furnaces and distillation column overhead systems.",
    "A DP transmitter measures the sum of two pressures at high-side and low-side connections and outputs a proportional 4–20 mA signal representing the average system pressure. Internally, both pressures act on the same side of a sensing diaphragm; the combined deflection proportional to the total pressure is converted to an electrical signal. DP transmitters are used to measure static pressure in compressed air headers, pressure vessel walls, and transmission pipeline main lines.",
    "A DP transmitter measures the ratio of two pressures at high-side and low-side connections and outputs a proportional 4–20 mA signal representing the compression ratio across a compressor stage. Internally, both pressures act on a logarithmic sensing element; the deflection proportional to the pressure ratio is converted to an electrical signal using a linearization algorithm. DP transmitters are used exclusively to measure compressor performance in gas turbine power plants and centrifugal refrigeration systems."
],
    correctIndex: 0,
    fullAnswer: "A DP transmitter measures the pressure difference between two points (high-side and low-side connections) and outputs a proportional 4–20 mA signal. Internally, both pressures act on opposite sides of a sensing diaphragm or capsule; the deflection proportional to the pressure difference is converted to an electrical signal. DP transmitters are used to measure flow (via orifice plates), level (via hydrostatic head), and pressure drop across filters or heat exchangers."
