    question: "How does a float-type level measurement system function? Describe the operating principle.",
    options: [
    "A float is a dense metallic sinker that rests on the vessel floor and rises or falls as level changes due to buoyancy force variation. Its weight is transmitted mechanically (via a tension cable or a hydraulic load cell) to an external weight indicator or level transmitter. In pneumatic float gauges, the weight of the float pressurizes a signal tube proportional to liquid level. Float methods are complex, intrusive, and suitable only for viscous liquids where other non-contact methods fail.",
    "A float is a buoyant device that rests on the liquid surface and rises or falls as level changes. Its position is transmitted mechanically (via a cable, rod, or lever arm) or magnetically (through a non-magnetic tube) to an external indicator or transmitter. In magnetic float gauges, a magnet inside the float rotates magnetic flags on the outside of a chamber, visually indicating level. Float methods are simple, reliable, and suitable for clean liquids.",
    "A float is a neutrally buoyant sealed sphere that remains suspended at a fixed depth within the liquid layer regardless of surface level changes. Its submerged position is detected optically (via a laser beam) or acoustically (via ultrasound) by sensors mounted on the vessel wall. In radar float gauges, the metallic sphere reflects microwave pulses back to the antenna with a delay proportional to the sphere's depth rather than its surface position. Float methods are highly accurate, non-intrusive, and suitable for turbulent or aerated liquids.",
    "A float is a pressurized gas-filled chamber that rests on the liquid surface and rises or falls as level changes, compressing or expanding a reference air column connected to a pressure indicator. Its buoyancy is transmitted pneumatically (via a purge tube or a bubbler system) to an external pressure gauge or transmitter. In electronic float gauges, the internal gas pressure of the float is monitored by a pressure sensor whose output is proportional to the liquid density rather than the liquid level. Float methods are highly accurate but require a dedicated instrument air supply at all times."
],
