    question: "Describe the physical operating principle of the ultrasonic level measurement method.",
    options: [
    "An ultrasonic level transmitter emits a high-frequency sound pulse from a transducer mounted above the liquid surface. The pulse travels through air, reflects off the liquid surface, and returns to the transducer. The instrument measures the time-of-flight (ToF) of the echo, and knowing the speed of sound in air, calculates the distance to the surface and thus the level. Ultrasonic measurement is non-contact, making it ideal for corrosive, dirty, or sticky liquids.",
    "An ultrasonic level transmitter emits a low-frequency electrical pulse from a transducer submerged below the liquid surface. The pulse travels through the liquid, reflects off the vessel roof, and returns to the transducer. The instrument measures the amplitude attenuation of the echo, and knowing the absorption coefficient of the liquid, calculates the path length and thus the level. Ultrasonic measurement is contact-type and immersed, making it ideal for clean, low-viscosity liquids only.",
    "An ultrasonic level transmitter emits a medium-frequency sound pulse from a transducer mounted on the side wall of the vessel at the minimum level point. The pulse travels horizontally through the liquid layer, reflects off the opposite vessel wall, and returns to the transducer. The instrument measures the resonant frequency of the standing wave formed between the two walls, and knowing the vessel internal diameter, calculates the liquid level from the number of half-wavelengths that fit within the measured path. Ultrasonic measurement is non-contact and unaffected by foam or surface turbulence.",
    "An ultrasonic level transmitter emits a high-frequency sound pulse from a transducer mounted on the external bottom of the vessel through the vessel wall. The pulse travels through the vessel wall and liquid, reflects off the liquid surface, and returns to the transducer. The instrument measures the phase shift of the reflected wave, and knowing the acoustic impedance of the vessel wall material, calculates the liquid level from the difference in propagation velocity. Ultrasonic measurement is non-intrusive and suitable for sealed pressurized vessels where no process connections are available."
],
