    "Radar level transmitters emit microwave pulses (typically 6–80 GHz for non-contact, lower for guided wave) that travel to the liquid surface and reflect back. The transmitter measures the time-of-flight of the reflected pulse to calculate the distance to the surface. Guided Wave Radar (GWR) uses a probe (rod or cable) inserted into the vessel to guide the microwave pulse, enabling measurement in turbulent, foamy, or low-dielectric media. Radar is highly accurate and unaffected by temperature, pressure, or vapor.",
    "Radar level transmitters emit infrared light pulses (typically 850–1550 nm wavelength for non-contact) that travel through air to the liquid surface and reflect back. The transmitter measures the amplitude of the reflected light beam to calculate the distance to the surface. Guided Wave Radar (GWR) uses a fiber optic probe inserted into the vessel to guide the infrared pulse, enabling measurement in dark, opaque, or highly reflective media. Radar is highly accurate but is affected significantly by condensation on the lens and surface foam.",
    "Radar level transmitters emit acoustic pulses (typically 40–200 kHz for non-contact) that travel through air to the liquid surface and reflect back. The transmitter measures the Doppler frequency shift of the reflected pulse to calculate the surface velocity and then integrates to find the level. Guided Wave Radar (GWR) uses an open-ended tube inserted into the vessel to channel the acoustic pulse, enabling measurement in pressurized vessels. Radar is highly accurate but is significantly affected by temperature, pressure, and vapor density changes.",
    "Radar level transmitters emit gamma radiation (137Cs or 60Co sources for non-contact) that travels through the vessel wall and liquid to a scintillation detector on the opposite side. The detector measures the radiation intensity reduction to calculate the liquid level by comparing to a full-vessel reference calibration. Guided Wave Radar (GWR) uses a collimating probe inserted into the vessel to direct the radiation beam along a known path length. Radar is highly accurate and unaffected by process conditions but requires radiation safety licensing and periodic source replacement."
