    "PWM is a technique for encoding an analog value in a digital signal by rapidly switching it between on and off states and varying the duty cycle — the ratio of on-time to the total period. A higher duty cycle delivers more average power to the load. Examples of use include motor speed control (by varying average voltage to the motor), LED dimming, audio signal generation, power converter switching (DC-DC converters, VFDs), and servo motor position control (where pulse width encodes angle).",
    "PWM is a technique for encoding a digital value in an analog signal by continuously varying the signal amplitude between minimum and maximum levels at a rate proportional to the digital input value. A higher amplitude delivers more instantaneous power to the load. Examples of use include analog-to-digital conversion (by comparing the ramp with the input and counting zero crossings), audio amplification (by linearly amplifying the analog carrier), power factor correction (by continuously adjusting the reactive current component), and Hall-effect sensor signal conditioning.",
    "PWM is a technique for encoding a frequency value in a digital pulse stream by varying the period of a fixed-width pulse rather than the pulse width itself — this is strictly pulse frequency modulation but is commonly mislabeled as PWM. A higher frequency delivers more energy per unit time to the load. Examples of use include stepper motor speed control (by varying pulse rate to the step driver), flow totalizer pulse output (by varying pulse rate proportional to volumetric flow), turbine meter signal processing, and thermocouple cold junction compensation circuits.",
    "PWM is a technique for encoding an analog value in a digital signal by counting the number of complete cycles of a reference frequency during a fixed measurement window — this is digital pulse counting rather than modulation. A higher count value represents a higher input analog level. Examples of use include frequency-to-voltage conversion (by integrating the pulse stream through an RC filter), tachometer signal processing (by counting pulses per revolution), encoder position feedback (by counting quadrature pulse edges), and proximity sensor output filtering."
