    "A fiber optic cable transmits data as pulses of light through a thin glass or plastic fiber (the core), surrounded by a cladding with a lower refractive index that keeps light inside by total internal reflection. Construction includes the core, cladding, buffer coating, and outer protective jacket. Advantages over copper include complete immunity to electromagnetic interference (EMI), no electrical hazard, very high bandwidth, very long transmission distances, and inherent security. Single-mode fiber (narrow core) is used for long distances; multi-mode for shorter runs.",
    "A fiber optic cable transmits data as pulses of electrical current through a thin copper alloy fiber (the core), surrounded by a dielectric insulating cladding with a higher resistivity than the core, which confines the current flow by the skin effect. Construction includes the copper core, polyethylene insulation, aluminum armoring, and outer LSZH jacket. Advantages over standard copper include lower electrical resistance per unit length, higher current-carrying capacity at high frequencies, and greater flexibility for repeated bending. Single-mode fiber (large diameter, 50 µm) is used for high-current applications; multi-mode (8 µm diameter) for low-current signal circuits.",
    "A fiber optic cable transmits data as modulated electromagnetic fields through a hollow metallic waveguide (the core), surrounded by a conductive outer shield with a lower surface impedance, which confines microwave energy by the boundary condition of the electric field being zero at the conductor surface. Construction includes the inner conductor, dielectric spacer rings, outer conductor, and corrugated protective sheath. Advantages over coaxial cable include lower attenuation at millimeter-wave frequencies, higher power handling capability, and immunity to external static fields. Single-mode fiber (rectangular waveguide) is used for low-order modes; multi-mode (circular waveguide) for high-order mode propagation.",
    "A fiber optic cable transmits data as continuous infrared laser beams through a hollow evacuated tube (the core), surrounded by reflective gold-coated inner walls that keep the laser beam inside by specular reflection at grazing angles. Construction includes the evacuated core, gold-coated reflective lining, vacuum isolation joints, and outer stainless steel pressure tube. Advantages over standard fiber include zero material dispersion, zero scattering loss, and operation at power levels impossible in solid-core fiber. Single-mode fiber (10 µm bore) is used for long-distance laser communication; multi-mode (50 mm bore) for high-power laser delivery in industrial cutting applications."
