    "UDP is a connectionless transport layer protocol that sends data packets (datagrams) without establishing a connection, without acknowledgment, and without guaranteed delivery or ordering. This makes it much faster and lower-latency than TCP. UDP is used where speed is more important than reliability — real-time applications such as video streaming, VoIP, live sensor broadcasting, and some industrial protocols. Unlike TCP, there is no retransmission of lost packets; the application layer must handle any necessary error correction.",
    "UDP is a connection-oriented transport layer protocol that establishes a dedicated virtual circuit before any data is transmitted, guaranteeing reserved bandwidth and bounded latency throughout the session. This makes it slower to set up than TCP but more predictable once connected. UDP is used where deterministic delivery timing is critical — industrial real-time control, audio/video conferencing with QoS guarantees, and PROFINET IRT. Unlike TCP, UDP includes a built-in retransmission mechanism but does not use sliding window flow control.",
    "UDP is a network layer addressing protocol that assigns unique identifiers to packets and routes them across multiple network hops from source to destination. Unlike TCP which operates only within a single local subnet, UDP provides end-to-end packet delivery across routers and ensures each packet arrives at the correct destination host. UDP uses 32-bit source and destination addresses; TCP uses 48-bit MAC addresses for the same purpose. UDP is slower than TCP for local network communication but essential for any communication crossing a router or subnet boundary.",
    "UDP is a session layer protocol that manages the establishment, coordination, and termination of dialog sessions between applications running on different hosts. Before data transfer, UDP negotiates session parameters including maximum transmission unit, compression algorithm, and authentication credentials via an initial handshake exchange. It uses session tokens and keep-alive messages to maintain the connection; idle sessions are terminated after a configurable timeout. UDP is used where long-lived, stateful communication sessions are required — database connections, secure shell sessions, and industrial historian data collection."
