    "Industrial Ethernet uses the IEEE 802.3 standard, typically at 100 Mbps (Fast Ethernet) or 1 Gbps, with deterministic protocols (PROFINET, EtherNet/IP) layered on top for real-time control. Common topologies in production include star (most robust, central switch), ring (redundancy via protocols like MRP or RSTP), line/daisy-chain (simple but single point of failure), and tree (hierarchical combination of stars). Industrial switches offer features like noise immunity, wide temperature range, DIN-rail mounting, and redundant power supplies.",
    "Industrial Ethernet uses the IEEE 802.11 standard (Wi-Fi), typically at 150 Mbps (802.11n) or 600 Mbps (802.11ac), with carrier-sense multiple access (CSMA/CA) providing inherent collision avoidance for real-time control. Common topologies in production include star (most robust, central access point), mesh (redundancy via automatic frequency selection), point-to-point (simple but limited to two devices), and ad-hoc (dynamic self-organizing network). Industrial access points offer features like antenna diversity, channel bonding, DIN-rail mounting, and PoE output.",
    "Industrial Ethernet uses the IEEE 802.15.4 standard (Zigbee), typically at 250 kbps (2.4 GHz band) or 20 kbps (868 MHz band), with TDMA providing deterministic time slots for real-time sensor data collection. Common topologies in production include star (most robust, central coordinator), mesh (redundancy via route discovery and self-healing), cluster-tree (hierarchical with router devices), and peer-to-peer (direct end-device communication). Industrial Zigbee modules offer features like frequency agility, AES-128 encryption, DIN-rail mounting, and USB gateway interface.",
