    "HART (Highway Addressable Remote Transducer) superimposes a digital FSK (Frequency Shift Keying) signal — using 1200 Hz for '1' and 2200 Hz for '0' — on top of the standard 4–20 mA analog current loop. The high-frequency AC digital signal averages to zero and does not disturb the DC analog measurement. This allows simultaneous analog measurement transmission and bidirectional digital communication (device configuration, diagnostics, secondary variables) over the same two wires without interrupting the process signal.",
    "HART (Highway Addressable Remote Transducer) replaces the 4–20 mA analog current loop entirely with a digital packet-switched current signal that encodes measurement data in 8-bit packets at 1200 baud. The digital signal fully replaces the analog component, which is only used as a power supply for the field device. This allows high-speed multivariable measurement transmission (up to 16 process variables) and bidirectional digital communication over the same two wires, but requires replacement of all existing 4–20 mA input cards with dedicated HART master cards.",
    "HART (Highway Addressable Remote Transducer) superimposes a digital ASK (Amplitude Shift Keying) signal — using 20 mA for logic '1' and 4 mA for logic '0' — directly modulating the 4–20 mA analog current. The digital signal uses the full current swing of the analog range, making simultaneous analog measurement impossible during digital communication bursts. This allows bidirectional digital communication when the analog measurement is interrupted by a hold-last-value function, and the control system must pause its PID calculation during each HART burst transmission.",
    "HART (Highway Addressable Remote Transducer) superimposes a digital OOK (On-Off Keying) signal — switching between 0 mA and 4 mA current pulses — on top of the standard 4–20 mA analog current loop at frequencies above 10 kHz. The ultra-high-frequency digital pulses are filtered out by the input impedance of standard control system analog input cards, leaving only the underlying 4–20 mA analog component undisturbed. This allows unidirectional upload-only digital communication from smart field devices to a handheld HART communicator that clips directly onto the field cable without requiring loop access."
