    "The Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) refers to the network of interconnected sensors, devices, machines, and software that communicate and share data over the internet within industrial environments, enabling advanced monitoring, analytics, and automation. Unlike traditional automation, IIoT leverages cloud computing, big data analytics, machine learning, and edge computing to extract actionable insights from vast amounts of process data. Key applications in smart manufacturing include predictive maintenance (detecting equipment failures before they occur), real-time quality control, digital twin simulation, energy management optimization, and supply chain visibility. IIoT ultimately drives increased efficiency, reduced downtime, and greater flexibility in manufacturing operations — forming the foundation of Industry 4.0.",
    "The Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) refers to the replacement of all wired SCADA and DCS infrastructure with a fully wireless, cloud-hosted control system where all PLCs, sensors, and actuators communicate exclusively via public 5G cellular networks. Unlike traditional automation, IIoT eliminates the need for on-premise servers, engineering workstations, and local HMI panels by moving all control logic to a centralized cloud PLC that executes IEC 61131-3 programs in a managed container environment. Key applications include eliminating control room infrastructure, reducing cybersecurity risks by removing all local network components, and enabling fully autonomous unmanned plant operations without any local operator presence. IIoT ultimately drives the complete elimination of traditional industrial automation hardware by 2035 — fulfilling the vision of Industry 5.0.",
